<subSubSection pageId="3" pageNumber="28" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="3.[151,1437,547,826]" pageId="3" pageNumber="28">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,266,547,574]" pageId="3" pageNumber="28">Diagnosis</emphasis>
. 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Zeller" authorityYear="1855" box="[280,409,548,574]" class="Insecta" family="Blastobasidae" genus="Blastobasis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="28" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[280,409,548,574]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="28">Blastobasis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is similar to 
<taxonomicName authority="Walsingham, 1907" authorityName="Walsingham" authorityYear="1907" box="[554,879,548,574]" class="Insecta" family="Blastobasidae" genus="Hypatopa" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="28" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[554,664,549,574]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="28">Hypatopa</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Walsingham, L." box="[670,879,548,574]" pageId="3" pageNumber="28" pagination="197 - 228" refId="ref18490" refString="Walsingham, L. (1907) Descriptions of new North American tineid moths, with a generic table of the family Blastobasidae. Proceedings of the United States national Museum, 33 (No. 1567), 197 - 228. https: // doi. org / 10.5479 / si. 00963801.1567.197" type="journal article" year="1907">
Walsingham, 
<quantity box="[823,879,548,574]" metricMagnitude="1" metricUnit="m" metricValue="4.84378" pageId="3" pageNumber="28" unit="in" value="1907.0">1907</quantity>
</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
in the male genitalia, but it can be separated from the latter by the male antenna with a notch in the first flagellomere, the gnathos with one or two denticles medially on the posterior margin, and the proximal flange not bulged in the male genitalia. In 
<taxonomicName authority="Walsingham, 1907" authorityName="Walsingham" authorityYear="1907" box="[1086,1196,621,646]" class="Insecta" family="Blastobasidae" genus="Hypatopa" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="28" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1086,1196,621,646]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="28">Hypatopa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
the first flagellomere of the antenna is not notched in male, the gnathos is smooth or notched medially on the posterior margin, and the proximal flange is bulged.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="3.[151,1437,547,826]" pageId="3" pageNumber="28">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,266,728,754]" pageId="3" pageNumber="28">Notes</emphasis>
. The ten species from Mainland 
<collectingCountry box="[653,720,728,754]" name="China" pageId="3" pageNumber="28">China</collectingCountry>
are similar to the 
<typeStatus box="[937,985,729,755]" pageId="3" pageNumber="28">type</typeStatus>
species 
<taxonomicName authority="(Zeller, 1839)" authorityName="Zeller" authorityYear="1839" baseAuthorityName="Zeller" baseAuthorityYear="1839" box="[1086,1404,728,754]" class="Insecta" family="Oecophoridae" genus="Oecophora" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="28" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="phycidella">
<emphasis box="[1086,1238,728,754]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="28">B. phycidella</emphasis>
(Zeller, 1839)
</taxonomicName>
in hindwing venation with M 
<subScript attach="left" box="[448,456,782,796]" fontSize="6" pageId="3" pageNumber="28">2</subScript>
and M 
<subScript attach="left" box="[535,543,782,796]" fontSize="6" pageId="3" pageNumber="28">3</subScript>
coincident (
<figureCitation box="[682,749,764,790]" captionStart="FIGURES 2−3" captionStartId="2.[151,264,1952,1977]" captionTargetBox="[171,1425,448,1782]" captionTargetId="figure@2.[155,1439,431,1798]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURES 2−3. Morphology of Blastobasis spp. 2, Head of B. sprotundalis, ♂; 3, Venation of B. drymosa, ♂, slide No. TKJ16231W. (Scale bars = 0.5 mm)" figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3468236" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3468236/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="28">Fig. 3</figureCitation>
), while the two veins are stalked in the most species from the Nearctic and Neotropical regions.
</paragraph>
